description:
PLEASE NOTE: The production version was released on 1.9.2024. Migration tutorial can be found here: https://developers.erstegroup.com/docs/tutorial/migration-to-new-api-version-premium-accounts-psd2-account-info

Accounts API is a HTTP-1.1 REST service that provides access to user and accounting data of Česká spořitelna, a.s. customers. It allows you to access general information about accounts, balances, services, transactions and even more.

Pricing

Access to Premium API is charged at 300 CZK per month for each connected account, as documented in our pricing list https://www.csas.cz/banka/content/inet/internet/cs/RR_MSE.ACH..xml,pdf_IE (section 3.5) and https://www.csas.cz/static_internet/cs/Komunikace/Oznameni/Oznameni/Prilohy/cenik_korporatni_klientela_cz_od_26_1_2024.pdf (section 4.5).

PLEASE NOTE: The pricing does not apply to natural persons' ("fyzická osoba (FO)") accounts.

Environments

This API is published on these environments:

  • sandbox https://webapi.developers.erstegroup.com/api/csas/public/sandbox/v3/accounts

  • production https://www.csas.cz/webapi/api/v3/accounts

Certificate and Signatures

Endpoint protection

This API does not require Certificate protection with 2-way SSL (QWAC).

Content signature

No content of this API needs to be signed with QSealC certificate.

resources.name: Transaction

actions.name: Get overview of transactions
actions.description:
Paginated and optionally filtered (by dates) transaction list for given account.

  • Paginated ✔

  • Sortable ✔

    • Fields: bookingdate, amount

  • Filtered ✔

    • fromDate, toDate
      • fromDate is not defined - only transactions for 1 month are returned (till toDate or present time)
      • fromDate is present - transactions from fromDate (including) till present or toDate are returned
      • fromDate is in future - Response 400 | DT01 | [InvalidDate] Invalid date value or format

Using the parameters fromDate and toDate

When using the fromDate and toDate filter query parameters, you can specify these dates in the YYYY-MM-DD format. These dates are interpreted according to the UTC (Coordinated Universal Time) time zone by default. This means that if you are operating in a different time zone and wish to apply these filters based on your local time, you will need to adjust the dates accordingly to match UTC time.

For instance, let's assume you're in the CET (Central European Time) zone and wish to set toDate to reflect the current date in your local time. If it is currently December 18, 2023, at 00:34 AM CET, you need to consider the time difference between CET and UTC. Since CET is typically 1 hour ahead of UTC (this can vary with daylight saving time adjustments), it would still be December 17, 2023, at 11:34 PM UTC. Therefore, to accurately set toDate based on your local (CET) date and time, you should input it as 2023-12-17, aligning with the current date and time in UTC.

This adjustment ensures that the API filters the data up to the end of the day on December 17, 2023, in UTC, which corresponds to the beginning of December 18, 2023, in CET. Always account for the time difference between your local time zone and UTC when setting these parameters to accurately reflect the desired date range.

resourceGroups.name: Certificate
resourceGroups.description:
Resource for obtaining a CSAS public certificate for fingerprint signature verificiation to confirm CSAS identity.

The fingerprint request header from the "Send Notification" endpoint will contain the JWT token. It will include:

  • JWT header
{
  "alg": "RS512"
}
  • JWT payload
{
  "notificationBody": {
    "accountId": "D2C8C1DCC51A3738538A40A4863CA288E0225E52",
    "notificationId": "22468790-78f4-444d-a65e-e1f17948eeb3",
    "transaction": {<this will contain the transaction details>}
  },
  "nonce": "a9c7b5e7-1e4e-4f33-a997-a6b3aeee815c",
  "timestamp": "1692777366"
}
  • JWT signature

You can find out how to validate the signature here - https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7519.

resourceGroups.name: Transaction notifications
resourceGroups.description:
You can create notifications for all of your enrolled accounts to get informed about incoming and outgoing transactions. This way, there is no need to call the GET Transactions endpoint to learn about new transactions as often. We still recommend cross-checking received notification against transaction history or statements for example once a day.

First, there are three endpoints for managing notifications - create, delete, list. Once a notification is created, you can delete it or get a list of existing notifications. After you create a notification, you need to implement another endpoint on your end which we will call when there is a new transaction. The payload you will receive is identical to one transaction from the array of transactions in the GET Transactions endpoint. Once you receive the notification, you can confirm the sender's identity with the fingerprint header by using the certificate from the GET Certificate endpoint.

resources.name: Transaction notifications - Send
resources.description: This endpoint describes how we send the notification to your notification URL. This will be the notificationURL you registered with us when creating the notification. You will need to implement this endpoint on your end and we will call it once there is a new transaction. In case our attempt to send a notification fails, we will try to resend it multiple times. Please note that in case of an outage on our side, we send notification retroactively, up to four hours old. The request headers you will receive will include a fingerprint header which contains a signed JWT token. You can use it to verify the notification was sent by CSAS by using the certificate from the GET Certificate endpoint described at Reference "Certificate". Please note that in the Notification URL, we only support HTTPS, in other words port 443.
